  "text": "Patients with liver disease receiving warfarin have poorer anticoagulation control and more bleeding [CITATION_1] . A 4-point score system has been proposed to identify patients with liver failure at higher risk for poor anticoagulation control and bleeding during warfarin therapy (one point each for albumin [2. those with liver disease and a score of zero had modestly lower TTR (56.7 %) but no increase in bleeding (hazard ratio, 1.16; p = 0.59), whereas those with liver disease and the worst score (4) had both poor control (29.4 %) and high risk of bleeding (hazard ratio 8.53; p \\ 0.001) [CITATION_2] . Warfarin should not be used in patients with liver disease who have multiple or serious medical comorbidities (e.g. advanced pulmonary/heart disease, advanced stage hepatocellular carcinoma, recent history of GI bleeding), history of multiple falls, and inability to closely monitor anticoagulation [CITATION_3] . In patients where the risk/benefit is Foods with a lot of vitamin K like broccoli, spinach, and green tea may interfere with warfarin; do not avoid foods with vitamin K, but try to maintain consistent dietary habits Alcohol increases the risk for bleeding and interferes with warfarin therapy; no more than 1-2 drinks per day, and avoid binge drinking For patients with a history of poor medication adherence we suggest warfarin is the preferred oral anticoagulant.",
